      • productAllButOne

        public static int[] productAllButOne​(int[] data)
        from GeeksForGeeks.com return an array (say prod) such that for all i, prod[i] is equal to the product of all the elements of data except data[i]. IMPORTANT!!! Solve it without division operator and in O(n). Example : if data = {10, 3, 5, 6, 2} then prod = {180, 600, 360, 300, 900}
        Parameters:
        data -
        Returns:
        array based on above specs

      • getLongestConsecutiveLength

        public static int getLongestConsecutiveLength​(int[] data)
        Parameters:
        data -
        Returns:
        length of the longest collection of consecutive items (in terms of value, not order) For example, if data = {0, 10, 3, -2, 5, 2, 1, 12, -1}, the longest collection of consecutive values is -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3 (6 items in total). so return 6.

      • getCommonItemsUnsorted

        public static int[] getCommonItemsUnsorted​(int[] a,
                                           int[] b)
        Parameters:
        a -
        b -
        Returns:
        an array containing the common items from a and b. If array a contains p occurrences of an item and array b contains q occurrences of the same item, the array returned must have Math.min(p, q) occurrences of that item. All occurrences of an item in the resulting array should be together, and be in the order of first appearance in array a. See the last junit test sample for details

      • longestMirroredSequence

        public static int[] longestMirroredSequence​(int[] data)
        Parameters:
        data -
        Returns:
        the longest sequence of items that occurs in the mirrored (back to front) form as well. in case of a tie, return the sequence that occurs first. Examples: if data = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 20, 10, 40, 30, 20, 50, 40} return the array {20, 30, 40} (not {40, 30, 20}) if data = {1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2} return the array {1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1} if data = {5,6,7,8,9} return the array {5} if data = {5,6,7,5,7,6,8,5,6,9} return the array {6,7}

      • getSet

        public static int[] getSet​(int[] data)
        in math, a "set" is defined as a collection of **distinct** items. Thus, {1,7,2,9} is a set, but {1,7,2,1,9} is not (since 1 occurs multiple times).
        Parameters:
        data -
        Returns:
        a "set" obtained from the passed array. the order of the items should be the order in of the first occurrences of the items in the passed array. for example, if data = {1,7,2,1,9,7,9,9}, return {1,7,2,9} if data = {7,2,1,1,9,7,9,9}, return {7,2,1,9}
